[6] India - Himachal Pradesh
Date: Wed 19 Feb 2020
Source: The Tribune, Tribune News Service [edited]
https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/swine-flu-rears-its-head-again-44369


Swine flu [influenza A/H1N1] has claimed its 1st victim this year [2020] while the number of cases has reached 11.

The Health Department has sounded an alert in the state [Himachal Pradesh], asking the chief medical officers to issue an advisory to the public to take preventive measures. According to the surveillance officer, [influenza A/H1N1] claimed the life of a patient at the PGI a few days ago. The patient belonged to Shimla [capital city of Himachal Pradesh].

As many as 11 patients -- 9 in Shimla, one each in Kangra and Mandi [districts in Himachal Pradesh state] -- have tested positive this year [2020], said Dr Sonam Negi, state disease surveillance officer.

The 2 [influenza A/H1N1] patients were admitted to the isolation ward of the IGMC [Indira Gandhi Medical College, Shimla] said a senior consultant of the hospital. Most of the [influenza A/H1N1] cases have been reported in Shimla for the last 5 days. Professor of Medicine, IGMC, Dr Jatinder Kumar Mokta said the [influenza A/H1N1] was a seasonal viral infection prevailing in the environment and that there was no cause for panic.

"This virus can be checked by maintaining personal hygiene and taking precautionary measures by patients. People should wash hands, avoid handshakes, and drink warm water, and the patients suffering from cold should take rest at home," Dr Mokta said.

"Patients and their attendants and staff are advised to wear masks," Dr Mokta said. "People should avoid visiting crowded places and wash their hands frequently and take a lot of liquids. They should use cover while sneezing and coughing," he added. Though the intensity of [influenza A/H1N1] as compared to last year [2019] is much less, the sudden spurt in the cases has sounded an alert, as weather has been changing fast.

In 2019-20, the [influenza A/H1N1] toll was 30, while the number of cases was 330 till [19 Feb 2020], said Dr Negi. But this year [2020], there was one death, while the numbers of cases were 11, he added. Dr Negi said that of 109 patients tested for [influenza A/H1N1], 69 were at the IGMC and 40 at the government medical college, Tanda. The CMOs [Chief Medical Officers] have been alerted. The January-March period is the flu season, Negi said.

[Byline: Kuldeep Chauhan]

